          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Charleston</placeName>, <date>July
                                                  11<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1852</date></p>
                              <p>My dear Sir,</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">Your esteemed favor I recd some time ago<lb/> but
                                        having nothing of importance to communicate I<lb/> delayed
                                        until I recd Amt of your Bill against KKBE.<lb/> which had
                                        been ordered for payment last month; —I shall<lb/> enclose
                                        it with amt due for Binding &amp;c.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I saw <persName>Rev M Myer</persName> yesterday
                                        and delivered your message<lb/> respecting the article in
                                        the Phillippson paper. <persName>D<hi rend="sup">r</hi>
                                                  Myer</persName> requested<lb/> me to state that he
                                        is <hi rend="underline">not the author</hi> of the Article
                                        in question<lb/> nor does he know who is, he intends to
                                        write you on the<lb/> Subject. I <del>notice</del> observe
                                        that you have noticed this attack<lb/> in the <add>?</add>
                                        of the Occident. Can you my friend expect<lb/> that your
                                        views should meet the approbation of the entire<lb/> public.
                                        I wish you would adopt the high and dignified course of
                                        allowing<lb/> the little dogs to bark—with out any regard to
                                        their noise.<lb/> I pray you to keep such articles out of
                                        your paper as <hi rend="underline">this</hi><lb/> the <hi
                                                  rend="underline">invitation for the</hi>
                                        <sic>anonimous</sic> correspondent of Asmoneon to<lb/> come
                                        forward with his name,—and your correspondents letter<lb/>
                                        from <placeName>New York</placeName> about <hi
                                                  rend="underline">your title of Revd</hi>
                                        <del>to Mr who I</del><lb/> What do the public care for
                                        these things, and it cannot<lb/> possibly add to your
                                        reputation;—I take the liberty to say<lb/> so much to you
                                        only for the purpose of bringing to your mind that<lb/>
                                        <add>?</add> the man &amp; his principles must be of some
                                        consequence if they<lb/> are publicly attacked, but that you
                                        should notice all these attacks<lb/> is as preposterous as
                                        it is <sic>unpracticable</sic>, in noticing them you<lb/>
                                        make them of consequence. (whether they are so or not)—<lb/>
                                        The sensitive plant: droops and yields to every breath of
                                        air, while the Oak resists the tempest.<lb/> blast.—and, on
                                        the morrow appear the fresher and more beautiful from the
                                        Encounter</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>may I call your attention to the resolution <add>?</add> I sent
                                        you<lb/> by <persName>M Valentine</persName>, <add>?</add>
                                        <persName>D<hi rend="sup">r</hi>. E</persName> to lecture,
                                        and the action of<lb/> the meeting <del>thereupon</del> on
                                                  <persName>Lyons</persName> resignation, its
                                        publication would<lb/> benefit our friend
                                                  <persName>Eckman</persName> more especially as the
                                        report<lb/> is current in <placeName>N Y.</placeName> that
                                                  <persName>D<hi rend="sup">r</hi>. E</persName> was
                                        the cause of <persName>Lyons</persName> resig<lb/>nation,
                                        the resolutions are public property and are officially<lb/>
                                        sent to you. (the remarks of <persName>Valentine</persName>
                                        you can omit if you<lb/> think proper. Merely state the
                                        reason for <persName>Lyons</persName> resigning that<lb/>
                                        the world may know the true cause. You also omitted<lb/> to
                                        publish the <del>letter of</del> circular of the Members of
                                        KKBE<lb/> (which I furnished you). Signed by a large number
                                        of friends<lb/> of <persName>D<hi rend="sup">r</hi>.
                                                  E.</persName> approving his course on resigning)
                                        the publication of this would<lb/> have done <persName>D<hi
                                                  rend="sup">r</hi>. E</persName> some permanent
                                        good. I suppose you have<lb/> overlooked it. I have been
                                        asked by very many of the<lb/>
                                        <add>?</add> why you hesitated to publish it, <hi
                                                  rend="underline">after promising me</hi><lb/>
                                        <hi rend="underline">that you would</hi>,</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I am highly delighted with your thoughts on the
                                        Jewish<lb/> Ministry. I rejoice that you have come out <hi
                                                  rend="underline">so boldly</hi><lb/> and denounced
                                        the present mode of <hi rend="underline">acting</hi> in
                                        our<lb/> synagogue in your <hi rend="underline">next</hi>
                                        tell them something about praying<lb/> in the language they
                                        understand, those who do not understand<lb/> the Hebrew and
                                        make a believe they pray in it because they recite them
                                        there prayers are of no use.<lb/> Advocate a portion of the
                                        prayers to be read in English<lb/> viz <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >the <add>?</add></hi> and then afterwards in
                                        Hebrew—and<lb/> the same with several others, so that the
                                                  <hi rend="underline">people</hi> may<lb/>
                                        understand some of the service. Where lip service is an<lb/>
                                        abomination, Now is the time to promulgate the<lb/> truth to
                                        the people.</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>I have recd <hi rend="underline">an invitation</hi> to the <hi
                                                  rend="underline">wedding</hi> of our mutual<lb/>
                                        friend <persName>S. Solis</persName>—this event so unlooked
                                        for and so sudden<lb/> took me rather by
                                        <sic>surprize</sic>. I trust he has acted with<lb/> his
                                        usual forethought and excellent <sic>judgement</sic>, in
                                        this<lb/> matter. “I hope the end will justify the means,”
                                        for fear<lb/> this remark may be misconstrued I explain it
                                        thus: I hope<lb/> marriage may be the means of prolonging
                                        his life and restoring<lb/> his health, amen, have you had
                                        time to think of this affair?<lb/> give me your views of his
                                        health when he returns,</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Dear <persName>Sarah</persName> has been quite
                                        indisposed she desires her kind regards.<lb/> the children
                                        are well.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(9)">Yours sincerely</p>
                              <p rend="indent(10)">
                                        <persName role="author">J. N. Carvalho</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p><addressee>Rev I Leeser</addressee>.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <placeName>Phil<hi rend="sup">a</hi></placeName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p>Editor Occident</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <placeName>Walnut St. near Thirteenth</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
